1
00:00:00,900 --> 00:00:02,300
<i>You want Andy
to be part of Hotel 88?</i>

2
00:00:02,600 --> 00:00:05,233
<i>He knows about Justin
and Juan.</i>

3
00:00:05,433 --> 00:00:07,767
<i>Andy thinks he's the
clever one.</i>

4
00:00:07,767 --> 00:00:09,233
<i> Well, let's see him try.</i>

5
00:00:09,233 --> 00:00:10,500
<i>We're making you a partner
of the hotel.</i>

6
00:00:10,667 --> 00:00:12,600
<i>Just do your part
and I'll do mine.</i>

7
00:00:13,867 --> 00:00:13,967
<i> And I want you to know</i>

8
00:00:14,433 --> 00:00:16,300
<i> And I want you to know</i>

9
00:00:16,300 --> 00:00:20,400
<i>that there's a hidden treasure
in this hotel.</i>

10
00:00:21,367 --> 00:00:22,867
<i>So, there's really
a hidden treasure.</i>

11
00:00:22,867 --> 00:00:24,900
<i>Our efforts won't be
for nothing.</i>

12
00:00:26,667 --> 00:00:28,567
<i>This is the beginning
of our search</i>

13
00:00:28,567 --> 00:00:31,467
<i>for the hidden treasure
at Hotel 88.</i>

14
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:36,833
This seems too long
for a passcode.

15
00:00:38,733 --> 00:00:41,333
Martin thinks it's a code
for a vault,

16
00:00:41,333 --> 00:00:43,767
but Papa didn't have
a vault.

17
00:00:44,933 --> 00:00:48,400
If it's a serial number,
we can check it online

18
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:50,533
and find out where
the compass came from.

19
00:01:01,933 --> 00:01:04,033
You were amazing
the other day.

20
00:01:04,033 --> 00:01:06,900
Huh? What's amazing
about that?

21
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:09,567
Nothing. It was like
you were in control,

22
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:13,100
and you knew what you
were saying and doing.

23
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:15,067
It's for our families.

24
00:01:15,067 --> 00:01:17,300
[GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING]

25
00:01:17,300 --> 00:01:19,700
I hope I'm brave like you.

26
00:01:22,767 --> 00:01:25,033
You're not just brave, Luna.

27
00:01:25,033 --> 00:01:26,200
You're also strong.

28
00:01:27,900 --> 00:01:30,500
You're the strongest woman
I've known.

29
00:01:32,567 --> 00:01:33,733
I have to.

30
00:01:35,100 --> 00:01:36,567
Ever since Leon
got imprisoned,

31
00:01:36,567 --> 00:01:38,000
I had to take over
as the eldest.

32
00:01:38,833 --> 00:01:40,667
I don't want to disappoint
my siblings.

33
00:01:41,767 --> 00:01:42,833
And Mom, too.

34
00:01:45,900 --> 00:01:47,367
You won't disappoint them.

35
00:01:49,667 --> 00:01:51,000
I'm here for you.

36
00:01:53,067 --> 00:01:54,133
Thank you.

37
00:01:54,133 --> 00:01:58,867
[GENTLE MUSIC CONTINUES]

38
00:01:58,867 --> 00:02:00,267
[JUSTIN] Luna.

39
00:02:00,467 --> 00:02:01,533
[LUNA CLEARS THROAT]

40
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:05,067
[JUSTIN] Did you get it?

41
00:02:05,067 --> 00:02:06,667
- Gio.
- Hmm?

42
00:02:09,700 --> 00:02:17,467
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

43
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:18,700
The map...

44
00:02:21,767 --> 00:02:23,900
The numbers
are coordinates?

45
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:25,067
It seems like it.

46
00:02:25,867 --> 00:02:27,100
But where is this?

47
00:02:28,833 --> 00:02:30,533
That's here in our province.

48
00:02:31,067 --> 00:02:32,633
Then let's go there.

49
00:02:34,867 --> 00:02:35,867
Let's go.

50
00:02:37,100 --> 00:02:44,033
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]

51
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:41,733
[SIGHS SHARPLY]

52
00:03:44,867 --> 00:03:46,533
Sir! No!

53
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,700
Why are you screaming?

54
00:03:49,700 --> 00:03:52,833
I saw you were going to
throw the monocular away.

55
00:03:52,833 --> 00:03:54,500
I wasn't going to throw it away.

56
00:03:55,567 --> 00:03:59,333
- Oh, you weren't?
- I was just thinking, okay?

57
00:04:06,600 --> 00:04:08,867
[SIGHS] I tried everything.

58
00:04:08,867 --> 00:04:10,900
I looked it up in the light,
in the dark,

59
00:04:10,900 --> 00:04:12,833
among the trees,
among the clouds...

60
00:04:12,833 --> 00:04:15,433
- What about the water, sir?
- It'll get ruined.

61
00:04:19,533 --> 00:04:22,033
I've run out of ideas, too.

62
00:04:22,933 --> 00:04:24,967
We've been trying to figure
it out since earlier.

63
00:04:25,967 --> 00:04:29,233
Maybe it's connected to the
compass that Gio has.

64
00:04:29,267 --> 00:04:30,433
How?

65
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:35,033
You'll look at it when you're at
the location of the coordinates?

66
00:04:35,033 --> 00:04:38,633
- Maybe it'll work.
- What if it doesn't?

67
00:04:40,400 --> 00:04:42,167
We can't afford
to waste time.

68
00:04:42,167 --> 00:04:47,533
[RESOLUTE MUSIC PLAYING]

69
00:04:47,533 --> 00:04:49,033
I have an idea, sir.

70
00:04:50,633 --> 00:04:52,067
Sir, do you trust me?

71
00:04:53,833 --> 00:04:55,067
It depends.

72
00:04:55,067 --> 00:04:57,067
Just answer yes or no.

73
00:04:57,067 --> 00:04:59,567
Do you trust me, sir?

74
00:04:59,567 --> 00:05:06,567
[RESOLUTE MUSIC CONTINUES]

75
00:05:14,667 --> 00:05:15,800
[MARTIN CLEARS THROAT]

76
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:21,733
Sir.

77
00:05:22,767 --> 00:05:24,667
Are you okay?

78
00:05:24,667 --> 00:05:26,267
Is there something
in your butt?

79
00:05:26,267 --> 00:05:28,033
What? No.

80
00:05:28,767 --> 00:05:31,500
I've been noticing
you seem uneasy.

81
00:05:32,433 --> 00:05:35,567
You should've told me it was
your grandpa who'll help us.

82
00:05:36,767 --> 00:05:38,100
Why, sir?

83
00:05:38,100 --> 00:05:39,833
- Don't you like Grandpa?
- Shh.

84
00:05:40,200 --> 00:05:42,833
Sari, keep it down.
He can hear you.

85
00:05:43,967 --> 00:05:46,933
His hearing isn't that good,
so it's okay.

86
00:05:47,800 --> 00:05:49,833
So, tell me.
Don't you like Grandpa?

87
00:05:49,833 --> 00:05:51,933
No, it's not that.

88
00:05:51,933 --> 00:05:53,833
If I had known we were
going to him,

89
00:05:53,833 --> 00:05:55,933
I could've brought
something.

90
00:05:56,967 --> 00:05:58,133
Something?

91
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:01,767
You want to give
Grandpa something?

92
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:06,333
Uh... Yes.

93
00:06:06,333 --> 00:06:07,867
Like a token.

94
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:10,833
We're asking for his
help, aren't we?

95
00:06:11,733 --> 00:06:14,067
[CHUCKLES] My grandfather
is a nice person.

96
00:06:14,067 --> 00:06:15,900
A simple thank you
will be enough.

97
00:06:16,533 --> 00:06:19,333
What did you say, Sari?
You want ginger tea?

98
00:06:19,333 --> 00:06:21,033
No, Grandpa. Never mind.

99
00:06:21,033 --> 00:06:24,633
Anyway, can you help
Sir Martin, Grandpa?

100
00:06:32,933 --> 00:06:33,967
Hmm.

101
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:37,867
I've seen it before.

102
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:42,000
I can't be wrong.

103
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:43,933
Here.

104
00:06:44,933 --> 00:06:45,900
[BOTONG GRUNTS]

105
00:06:46,100 --> 00:06:47,667
[SARI] What are you
looking for, Grandpa?

106
00:06:47,667 --> 00:06:50,367
Do you want me
to help you? I'll help you.

107
00:06:51,633 --> 00:06:58,367
[STIRRING MUSIC PLAYING]

108
00:07:01,167 --> 00:07:02,333
Finally!

109
00:07:03,300 --> 00:07:05,067
Finally!

110
00:07:05,067 --> 00:07:06,867
This is the answer!

111
00:07:07,933 --> 00:07:11,767
[SARI] Don Ignacio delos Reyes
y Figueroa?

112
00:07:12,967 --> 00:07:18,167
He is the fifth governor-general
of the Philippines.

113
00:07:19,133 --> 00:07:21,233
During his term,

114
00:07:21,233 --> 00:07:25,267
he surveyed the land
in the east.

115
00:07:25,267 --> 00:07:26,267
Here.

116
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:29,000
Do you see
what he's holding?

117
00:07:29,833 --> 00:07:31,267
Do you see that?

118
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:39,567
It looks like this monocular.

119
00:07:40,433 --> 00:07:44,133
Because that one
and this one...

120
00:07:44,133 --> 00:07:45,400
are the same.

121
00:07:46,367 --> 00:07:48,367
That's an antique, Grandpa.

122
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:51,900
It's the antique
of all antiques.

123
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:54,233
But what does it have to do
with the hidden treasure

124
00:07:54,233 --> 00:07:56,833
aside from it being
the same monocular?

125
00:07:57,933 --> 00:08:02,133
He was the most corrupt
governor-general in history.

126
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:05,367
[BOTONG] He had dug up
and seized

127
00:08:05,367 --> 00:08:07,333
all the gold
in the Philippines

128
00:08:07,333 --> 00:08:11,000
and neighboring
countries in the east.

129
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:12,733
And they say...

130
00:08:13,733 --> 00:08:18,833
he had this treasure hidden
in our island until his death.

131
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,733
And that's what Papa
was looking for.

132
00:08:24,967 --> 00:08:28,300
It's not just your father.
There are others looking for it.

133
00:08:29,033 --> 00:08:30,767
But your father...

134
00:08:31,967 --> 00:08:34,000
was the luckiest.

135
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,333
Perhaps it was
because of his generosity

136
00:08:37,333 --> 00:08:44,133
that destiny granted him and
his friend a favor.

137
00:08:45,467 --> 00:08:47,767
So, what now, Grandpa?

138
00:08:47,767 --> 00:08:50,933
Their father left this clue.

139
00:08:50,933 --> 00:08:54,100
How will we know where the
treasure is using this?

140
00:08:54,100 --> 00:09:01,067
[STIRRING MUSIC PLAYING]

141
00:09:08,833 --> 00:09:09,933
Grandpa.

142
00:09:10,433 --> 00:09:11,400
Grandpa.

143
00:09:12,233 --> 00:09:13,733
Grandpa, where are you going?

144
00:09:16,533 --> 00:09:17,900
Where are you going?

145
00:09:20,267 --> 00:09:27,267
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

146
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:37,133
Oh my god. Martin is going
to kill me.

147
00:09:37,433 --> 00:09:38,633
You know, I don't get you.

148
00:09:39,267 --> 00:09:41,867
I asked you if you wanted
to go, you said yes.

149
00:09:41,867 --> 00:09:43,200
And now you're suddenly
worried?

150
00:09:43,267 --> 00:09:44,733
I know.

151
00:09:44,733 --> 00:09:47,233
You're right that we should
do something.

152
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:51,333
Yeah. I mean, they're
all doing something

153
00:09:51,333 --> 00:09:53,900
to find that
hidden treasure.

154
00:09:54,933 --> 00:09:57,400
- Just focus, okay?
- Yeah.

155
00:09:57,767 --> 00:09:58,767
Come on, let's go.

156
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:07,100
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

157
00:10:07,133 --> 00:10:08,367
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

158
00:10:11,367 --> 00:10:12,933
There's someone following us!
Come on, hurry!

159
00:10:15,133 --> 00:10:22,067
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

160
00:10:28,400 --> 00:10:29,833
Shh!

161
00:10:32,933 --> 00:10:39,867
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

162
00:10:47,133 --> 00:10:54,033
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

163
00:10:54,033 --> 00:10:55,100
- [SCREAMING]
- [THUDS]

164
00:10:56,067 --> 00:10:59,167
[OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

165
00:11:00,033 --> 00:11:01,933
- Ahh!
- Raphie!

166
00:11:01,933 --> 00:11:03,500
[TRIXIE] Shh!

167
00:11:03,967 --> 00:11:05,133
Raphie!

168
00:11:05,133 --> 00:11:06,833
Why did you pop up
out of nowhere?

169
00:11:06,833 --> 00:11:08,367
Guys!

170
00:11:08,967 --> 00:11:11,367
Sir Martin told me to keep
an eye on you guys.

171
00:11:11,367 --> 00:11:13,633
Girl, my CCTV eyes
saw you leave,

172
00:11:13,767 --> 00:11:14,933
so I followed you.

173
00:11:14,933 --> 00:11:16,367
[LAUGHS NERVOUSLY]

174
00:11:16,367 --> 00:11:18,300
Martin's seriously
going to kill me.

175
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:21,067
Sis, you won't tell our brothers
about this, right?

176
00:11:21,067 --> 00:11:22,633
Oh, no way.

177
00:11:22,633 --> 00:11:25,000
I can still win Sir Kiko over
with my charms.

178
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:26,333
But Sir Martin?

179
00:11:26,333 --> 00:11:28,633
We're dead.
He's going to scold us.

180
00:11:28,633 --> 00:11:29,700
[SIGHS]

181
00:11:29,700 --> 00:11:31,233
Oh...

182
00:11:31,700 --> 00:11:34,467
Come on, bosses' sisters.

183
00:11:34,467 --> 00:11:36,667
Let's get out of this place.
Come on.

184
00:11:36,667 --> 00:11:38,767
Please, let's leave.

185
00:11:38,967 --> 00:11:41,333
Let's just go back to the hotel.

186
00:11:43,133 --> 00:11:44,667
We might as well...

187
00:11:44,667 --> 00:11:45,867
Uhm?

188
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:47,567
What do you mean by that?

189
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:50,700
- I like your thinking.
- Hey!

190
00:11:50,700 --> 00:11:52,867
We're getting scolded anyway,
so let's go all out.

191
00:11:52,867 --> 00:11:54,267
No, no...

192
00:11:54,267 --> 00:11:55,867
Let's just go home,
ma'am, please.

193
00:11:55,867 --> 00:11:58,567
Darn it, I should've sent
Monette instead.

194
00:11:58,567 --> 00:12:00,867
Come on, let's go.
This way, please.

195
00:12:00,867 --> 00:12:02,300
Come on, Raphie!

196
00:12:02,300 --> 00:12:03,600
[SIGHS]

197
00:12:05,133 --> 00:12:06,500
Uh, hey! It's over here!

198
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:09,233
Sorry, sorry!
It's this way, come on!

199
00:12:09,233 --> 00:12:10,833
- Where is it...
- It's here. Sorry!

200
00:12:10,833 --> 00:12:12,200
You're spacing out!

201
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:13,333
Just go!

202
00:12:15,533 --> 00:12:16,833
Hey.

203
00:12:16,833 --> 00:12:18,633
We don't really need
to bring that much stuff.

204
00:12:19,300 --> 00:12:20,667
Better safe than sorry.

205
00:12:21,767 --> 00:12:24,500
What if we end up staying
there overnight, right?

206
00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:25,700
Alright then.

207
00:12:26,667 --> 00:12:27,833
Give me that.

208
00:12:32,333 --> 00:12:34,467
It's okay if Justin comes
with us, right?

209
00:12:36,167 --> 00:12:37,300
Yeah, it's fine.

210
00:12:38,300 --> 00:12:40,433
As long as he doesn't
get pissed at me.

211
00:12:40,433 --> 00:12:41,533
Gio...

212
00:12:43,633 --> 00:12:44,600
I know.

213
00:12:45,967 --> 00:12:48,600
I know your brother and I are
always butting heads, but...

214
00:12:49,200 --> 00:12:50,900
I'm not gonna criticize
everything he does.

215
00:12:52,067 --> 00:12:54,767
But we have to keep us
a secret from them first, okay?

216
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:57,700
We're not leaving to go
on vacation.

217
00:12:59,333 --> 00:13:01,667
And what we're doing
is for our families.

218
00:13:02,433 --> 00:13:03,567
Mhm...

219
00:13:04,100 --> 00:13:06,300
Thank you so much!

220
00:13:07,633 --> 00:13:08,900
Don't worry.

221
00:13:09,067 --> 00:13:11,733
After all this is over,
we can finally tell them.

222
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:15,600
[CHUCKLES]

223
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:17,200
Alright.
I'll just go change first.

224
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:34,533
Sari, can you hold this
for me first?

225
00:13:34,533 --> 00:13:36,400
Oh, and my cane too.

226
00:13:36,867 --> 00:13:38,167
Okay.

227
00:13:40,233 --> 00:13:45,100
[PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING]

228
00:13:45,733 --> 00:13:46,900
[BOTONG]
I can't see anything.

229
00:13:50,300 --> 00:13:51,533
Grandpa, the cover's still on.

230
00:13:51,700 --> 00:13:53,333
Sari, stop butting in.

231
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:55,700
You're so grumpy, Grandpa.

232
00:14:00,367 --> 00:14:03,833
We need to wait for the
golden light to arrive.

233
00:14:05,333 --> 00:14:06,667
Golden light?

234
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,233
In simple terms, sunset.

235
00:14:11,567 --> 00:14:13,600
[SARI] But Grandpa, why does it
have to be at a specific time?

236
00:14:15,733 --> 00:14:17,400
- Grandpa?
- Mhm?

237
00:14:19,767 --> 00:14:20,767
Go ahead.

238
00:14:36,933 --> 00:14:44,167
[PENSIVE MUSIC CONTINUES]

239
00:14:46,733 --> 00:14:49,733
Scientifically,
when the sun is high,

240
00:14:49,733 --> 00:14:51,400
the light scatters.

241
00:14:51,400 --> 00:14:53,467
But during sunrise or sunset,

242
00:14:53,467 --> 00:14:55,200
the sunlight hits at an angle.

243
00:14:55,200 --> 00:14:56,367
There's contrast.

244
00:14:59,267 --> 00:15:00,367
Look.

245
00:15:03,567 --> 00:15:06,567
This cover acts like a filter.

246
00:15:07,333 --> 00:15:09,867
It concentrates the light
directly onto the carving.

247
00:15:11,067 --> 00:15:13,933
This cap is designed as a
directional aperture filter.

248
00:15:14,200 --> 00:15:15,967
It's not magic or some mystery.

249
00:15:15,967 --> 00:15:17,867
It's an optical alignment
device.

250
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:23,767
[PENSIVE MUSIC CONTINUES]

251
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:26,733
That's making
my nose bleed, sir.

252
00:15:27,433 --> 00:15:29,300
But sure, yeah. Fine.

253
00:15:30,033 --> 00:15:30,933
Here.

254
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:33,667
Same here.
I got confused too.

255
00:15:34,500 --> 00:15:36,833
But... you're right.
You're right!

256
00:15:38,167 --> 00:15:40,467
[MARTIN] I just learned it
back in school.

257
00:15:41,367 --> 00:15:43,867
In my photography class
in college.

258
00:15:43,867 --> 00:15:44,967
[BOTONG] And because of that...

259
00:15:48,500 --> 00:15:50,867
we shall wait...

260
00:15:50,867 --> 00:15:54,667
...for the arrival
of the golden hour.

261
00:15:54,667 --> 00:16:01,500
[PENSIVE MUSIC CONTINUES]

262
00:16:02,633 --> 00:16:03,733
[WHISPERS] Hurry.

263
00:16:04,167 --> 00:16:05,167
[RAPHIE] Ow.

264
00:16:05,733 --> 00:16:07,467
Let's just go home, girls,
please!

265
00:16:07,467 --> 00:16:09,533
I love my life.
I don't want it ending here.

266
00:16:09,833 --> 00:16:11,767
You know, Raphie,
we're already here.

267
00:16:11,767 --> 00:16:13,433
Why back out now? Besides...

268
00:16:13,433 --> 00:16:17,633
maybe we'll find evidence
that could help Leon's case.

269
00:16:17,967 --> 00:16:19,967
What evidence?
Stop looking for evidence!

270
00:16:19,967 --> 00:16:21,033
Are you cops or something?

271
00:16:21,033 --> 00:16:22,867
Raphie, this is where
Juan was locked up

272
00:16:22,867 --> 00:16:23,700
when he got kidnapped.

273
00:16:24,133 --> 00:16:25,933
- That's exactly it.
- [CLATTERS]

274
00:16:25,933 --> 00:16:26,900
- Hey!
- Let's go!

275
00:16:27,200 --> 00:16:28,200
Hurry up!

276
00:16:28,200 --> 00:16:33,233
[OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

277
00:16:34,667 --> 00:16:35,967
Yeah, I'm already here.

278
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:37,900
Yeah.

279
00:16:38,767 --> 00:16:39,767
Okay, alright, alright.

280
00:16:39,767 --> 00:16:46,633
[OMINOUS MUSIC CONTINUES]

281
00:16:53,167 --> 00:16:54,967
[JADE] "Those that were
not taken by light."

282
00:16:54,967 --> 00:16:57,400
[PAGES FLIPPING]

283
00:16:57,400 --> 00:17:02,300
[BIRDS CHIRPING IN DISTANCE]

284
00:17:03,133 --> 00:17:04,667
Well? Did you get
the clue, Jade?

285
00:17:06,033 --> 00:17:07,200
[KIKO] Me too.

286
00:17:07,200 --> 00:17:09,500
I've read it several times,
but I still don't get it.

287
00:17:11,400 --> 00:17:12,333
Wait.

288
00:17:13,067 --> 00:17:13,933
Why...

289
00:17:14,700 --> 00:17:15,900
Kiko, look at this.

290
00:17:16,733 --> 00:17:18,633
Why are there
highlighted words?

291
00:17:20,367 --> 00:17:21,500
You're right.

292
00:17:21,500 --> 00:17:24,033
[MOROSE MUSIC PLAYING]

293
00:17:24,033 --> 00:17:26,167
What are those words
again? "In..."

294
00:17:27,233 --> 00:17:28,300
"In five...

295
00:17:29,900 --> 00:17:31,300
- Hmm?
- there are standing."

296
00:17:33,467 --> 00:17:35,600
"But doesn't walk."

297
00:17:37,433 --> 00:17:38,933
[KIKO] "But..."

298
00:17:40,167 --> 00:17:41,067
Jade.

299
00:17:42,133 --> 00:17:44,100
It formed a sentence.

300
00:17:44,567 --> 00:17:45,533
What's that again?

301
00:17:46,900 --> 00:17:49,167
"In five,
there are standing,

302
00:17:49,667 --> 00:17:51,233
but doesn't walk."

303
00:17:53,767 --> 00:17:55,433
Let's keep looking.

304
00:17:55,433 --> 00:17:57,000
We might find more.

305
00:17:57,067 --> 00:17:58,533
Okay, that might be the clue.

306
00:17:59,967 --> 00:18:06,933
[MOROSE MUSIC CONTINUES]

307
00:18:20,633 --> 00:18:22,767
- Is that the last one?
- Yes.

308
00:18:24,233 --> 00:18:26,167
"Oscalara."

309
00:18:29,233 --> 00:18:32,100
- Wait, let's read it again.
- Okay.

310
00:18:33,600 --> 00:18:36,700
[JADE] "In five, there are
standing but doesn't walk,

311
00:18:37,533 --> 00:18:40,533
follow the path
of the unwavering.

312
00:18:40,700 --> 00:18:43,067
The secret doesn't rest
on the paper,

313
00:18:43,700 --> 00:18:46,133
but at the back
molded by time.

314
00:18:47,333 --> 00:18:49,967
Read the drawing
like a vow

315
00:18:50,533 --> 00:18:52,967
because that is where...

316
00:18:54,067 --> 00:18:55,333
the Oscalara breathes."

317
00:18:56,767 --> 00:18:57,667
Jade, that was amazing.

318
00:18:58,600 --> 00:19:00,067
- We got the clue.
- Wait.

319
00:19:00,067 --> 00:19:01,000
I still don't get it.

320
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:02,567
So, what does that
mean?

321
00:19:04,233 --> 00:19:06,733
Maybe it's a place.

322
00:19:06,733 --> 00:19:08,433
It mentioned something
about a path.

323
00:19:09,667 --> 00:19:13,033
Isn't this what Luna
should be looking?

324
00:19:15,100 --> 00:19:17,233
[KIKO] The clues lead
to a place?

325
00:19:18,733 --> 00:19:19,733
I guess that's possible.

326
00:19:20,667 --> 00:19:27,633
[UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING]

327
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:44,167
But we're still not sure
that it's here in our place.

328
00:19:44,167 --> 00:19:47,200
But... Where could that be?

329
00:19:47,200 --> 00:19:49,367
- I don't know either.
- Let me read that again.

330
00:19:52,500 --> 00:19:56,500
[PHONE RINGING]

331
00:19:56,700 --> 00:19:58,500
You know what to do.

332
00:19:59,900 --> 00:20:00,933
Yes.

333
00:20:02,400 --> 00:20:05,467
Finding the treasure
is our priority.

334
00:20:06,600 --> 00:20:10,133
And Leon, as well.

335
00:20:10,133 --> 00:20:13,667
[PHONE RINGING CONTINUES]

336
00:20:16,767 --> 00:20:17,800
[JADE SIGHS SHARPLY]

337
00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:24,767
[UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING]

338
00:20:30,967 --> 00:20:32,233
[JUSTIN] Luna, where should
we go?

339
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:34,433
I don't know.

340
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:36,533
Here.

341
00:20:38,967 --> 00:20:40,267
This is the spot.

342
00:20:43,367 --> 00:20:46,767
Well, what are we waiting for?
Let's start digging.

343
00:20:46,767 --> 00:20:47,433
Here?

344
00:20:52,300 --> 00:20:53,233
Oh.

345
00:20:55,267 --> 00:20:57,533
I just went to the restroom,
and you're already asleep?

346
00:20:59,467 --> 00:21:01,967
I bet you've been feeling
sleepy since earlier.

347
00:21:07,067 --> 00:21:08,833
You must be tired.

348
00:21:16,433 --> 00:21:23,400
[PHONE RINGING]

349
00:21:33,300 --> 00:21:34,467
This is Kiko.

350
00:21:35,667 --> 00:21:36,500
Let's meet.

351
00:21:44,767 --> 00:21:46,600
- [SARI] Sir.
- [MARTIN] Thank you.

352
00:21:53,500 --> 00:21:55,300
That's a lot of water, sir.

353
00:21:55,300 --> 00:21:56,767
Careful, you might drink
too much.

354
00:21:57,433 --> 00:21:58,367
Hmm...

355
00:21:59,033 --> 00:22:01,167
Feels like I've heard you
say that before.

356
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:03,467
Ah...

357
00:22:03,867 --> 00:22:05,167
Yeah, sir.

358
00:22:05,167 --> 00:22:06,700
When you got drunk.

359
00:22:07,867 --> 00:22:10,600
I told you back then that
you were drinking too much.

360
00:22:11,167 --> 00:22:13,967
Then you said, "Just leave."

361
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:16,500
"I don't want you to stay."

362
00:22:16,900 --> 00:22:18,533
[CHUCKLES] That's embarrassing.

363
00:22:18,533 --> 00:22:19,767
Did I really say that?

364
00:22:19,867 --> 00:22:20,933
Yeah, sir.

365
00:22:21,067 --> 00:22:22,867
And a whole lot more.

366
00:22:23,067 --> 00:22:24,000
Like what?

367
00:22:25,867 --> 00:22:26,867
[SIGHS]

368
00:22:27,633 --> 00:22:29,267
"You're really so stubborn.

369
00:22:29,833 --> 00:22:31,433
Just leave me alone!"

370
00:22:33,133 --> 00:22:34,100
- What else?
- [CLEARS THROAT]

371
00:22:34,567 --> 00:22:35,600
Hmm...

372
00:22:36,233 --> 00:22:37,133
Oh...

373
00:22:38,433 --> 00:22:40,367
"You're no longer an asset,
Martin.

374
00:22:41,800 --> 00:22:43,000
You're a liability."

375
00:22:45,633 --> 00:22:47,633
Looks like I said a lot
of embarrassing things.

376
00:22:49,400 --> 00:22:50,667
[SARI]
Don't be embarrassed, sir.

377
00:22:51,067 --> 00:22:52,833
That wasn't really you talking.

378
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:53,833
Even so.

379
00:22:54,367 --> 00:22:56,967
Now you know the story
between me and my stepdad.

380
00:22:58,033 --> 00:23:00,367
Sir... that's family stuff.

381
00:23:01,033 --> 00:23:04,400
Everyone's got something
like that in their family.

382
00:23:06,933 --> 00:23:08,033
But, sir...

383
00:23:09,333 --> 00:23:10,900
can I say something?

384
00:23:11,400 --> 00:23:13,100
Could I stop you?

385
00:23:15,900 --> 00:23:17,667
I just want to say...

386
00:23:18,333 --> 00:23:19,933
what you said isn't true.

387
00:23:20,900 --> 00:23:22,700
That you will never be
good enough.

388
00:23:25,433 --> 00:23:28,233
Maybe your stepdad just had
too many expectations.

389
00:23:29,633 --> 00:23:31,800
That's why you keep thinking
you're not enough.

390
00:23:33,600 --> 00:23:34,567
But honestly, sir...

391
00:23:35,033 --> 00:23:36,500
you don't even realize it.

392
00:23:36,733 --> 00:23:38,600
To some people out there,

393
00:23:39,533 --> 00:23:40,767
you are more than enough.

394
00:23:44,833 --> 00:23:46,367
Feels like that's the first time
I've ever heard that.

395
00:23:46,800 --> 00:23:50,433
[SOFT MUSIC PLAYING]

396
00:23:50,567 --> 00:23:51,700
Absolutely, sir!

397
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:53,233
At least to me...

398
00:23:53,600 --> 00:23:56,867
A-and to your siblings too.

399
00:23:57,600 --> 00:23:59,667
Even after all those years
apart,

400
00:24:00,400 --> 00:24:01,767
they still accepted you.

401
00:24:02,300 --> 00:24:03,933
Unlike your stepdad.

402
00:24:06,833 --> 00:24:07,900
Thank you, Sari.

403
00:24:08,967 --> 00:24:10,633
It's nice to hear that
from somebody.

404
00:24:10,633 --> 00:24:17,567
[SOFT MUSIC CONTINUES]

405
00:24:22,600 --> 00:24:23,767
[BOTONG] It's time!

406
00:24:26,733 --> 00:24:28,833
Grandpa, not yet.

407
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:31,267
The golden light...

408
00:24:32,267 --> 00:24:33,867
...has arrived.

409
00:24:35,500 --> 00:24:37,867
Go ahead, Martin.
You take a look.

410
00:24:37,867 --> 00:24:39,133
Thank you, sir.

411
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:49,333
[BRIGHT MUSIC PLAYING]

412
00:24:50,533 --> 00:24:51,633
[MARTIN] Sari.

413
00:24:57,267 --> 00:24:59,833
[SARI] The mountain!
Grandpa, the mountain!

414
00:24:59,833 --> 00:25:03,367
[BRIGHT MUSIC CONTINUES]

415
00:25:03,400 --> 00:25:07,000
[BOTONG]
That is Mount Arelag.

416
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:09,933
And at the summit
of that mountain...

417
00:25:10,733 --> 00:25:13,900
stands a very special shrine.

418
00:25:18,700 --> 00:25:20,967
A shrine, Grandpa?
Like an actual shrine?

419
00:25:21,667 --> 00:25:23,500
Yes, my dear.

420
00:25:25,267 --> 00:25:26,800
And that...

421
00:25:27,400 --> 00:25:29,033
...is what you must find,
Martin.

422
00:25:30,700 --> 00:25:31,833
Thank you.

423
00:25:32,067 --> 00:25:33,367
Thank you so much.

424
00:25:41,067 --> 00:25:48,133
[BRIGHT MUSIC CONTINUES]

425
00:25:51,233 --> 00:25:53,433
<i>You're only going to
make it worse for Jade!</i>

426
00:25:53,433 --> 00:25:54,500
<i> That's none of your business!</i>

427
00:25:54,500 --> 00:25:55,933
<i> If you really cared about her,</i>

428
00:25:56,033 --> 00:25:57,700
<i>you'd think about
the situation she's in.</i>

429
00:25:57,700 --> 00:25:59,167
<i> I want to believe you, Dad.</i>

430
00:25:59,167 --> 00:26:01,300
<i>I'm doing the right thing
for you, Jade.</i>

431
00:26:01,300 --> 00:26:02,667
<i> They have a female accomplice?</i>

432
00:26:02,667 --> 00:26:04,733
<i> That voice sounds familiar.</i>

433
00:26:04,733 --> 00:26:06,300
<i> Hey, Raphie, what is it?!</i>

434
00:26:06,933 --> 00:26:07,767
<i> Shh!</i>

435
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:10,500
<i>Are you sure we got
the coordinates right?</i>

436
00:26:11,067 --> 00:26:12,233
<i> What if...</i>

437
00:26:13,067 --> 00:26:14,300
<i> I flip it around?</i>

438
00:26:17,067 --> 00:26:18,367
<i> He's alive.</i>

439
00:26:18,367 --> 00:26:20,400
<i> He's here on the island.</i>
